complaints.summary: While driving through the middle of a busy intersection, my 2013 Audi RS5 suddenly lost all power and was unable to engage any gears. The car came to a stop in active cross-traffic with vehicles approaching from multiple directions. I could not restart or move the car under its own power and had to push it to safety with the help of a passerby. Component that failed: Transmission / Power Train – specifically the DL501 S-Tronic Mechatronic Unit (Transmission Control Module). The part is still available for inspection at the dealership. Safety risk: This failure caused a complete loss of propulsion in active traffic, putting both myself and other drivers at risk of a collision. Dealer confirmation: The issue has been inspected and confirmed by an Audi dealership (Audi North Houston). The diagnostic code was P060A00 – “Internal Control Module Processor Performance.” Manufacturer documentation: Audi has previously issued Technical Service Bulletins 35-13-15 and 37-13-17, which identify this same defect as an internal circuit board failure and delamination in the DL501 mechatronic unit. Manufacturer response: Audi of America declined goodwill assistance despite acknowledging a previous case and documentation of this known failure mode. Warning or prior symptoms: A “Gearbox Malfunction – You may continue driving” warning briefly appeared moments before the car lost all power. After stopping, the vehicle could not be restarted or driven, leaving it immobilized in the intersection. Availability for inspection: The failed components and diagnostic report remain available through the Audi dealership that inspected the vehicle.

Vehicle: 2013 Audi RS5 Recall Reference: 37P1 / 37K8 (Transmission Control Module Software Update)  After Audi performed the TCM software update for recall 37P1/37K8, my vehicle began displaying “Transmission Overheating – Please Drive Conservatively” warnings during normal driving, especially in stop-and-go traffic.  This problem never occurred before the recall update. The warning now happens intermittently, raising concerns about: •Loss of drivability and safety risk if the transmission overheats while driving. •Premature failure of the transmission or mechatronic unit due to repeated overheating. •A direct link to the recall software update, since the issue began only after it was installed.  I am concerned that the recall fix created new drivability and safety problems. Audi has not provided a remedy.

My 2013 Audi rs5 has a well known transmission issue. There was a class action lawsuit that justs settled for earlier years of the S4 & S5 models.  My tranmission error has occurred several times when reversing, especially reversing up an incline or stop start reverses. The gear changes have become very jerky, both upshifts and downshifts, especially noticable at low speeds. The mechatronic unit on this audi model is a known issue and the audi forums are littered with examples of these mech units going bad. A replacement mech unit is costing me $4500 total and I have seen similar costs to others in the audi online forums like audizine

I WAS DRIVING ON THE HIGHWAY WHEN I GOT A "TRANSMISSION MALFUNCTION YOU CAN CONTINUE DRIVING" MESSAGE ON MY DISPLAY.  I SCANNED THE CAR WHEN I GOT HOME AND GOT THESE ERROR MESSAGE: (DRIVE POSITION SENSOR ELECTRICAL ERROR)  ' DTC P0700 (TRANSMISSION CONTROL SYSTEM MALFUNCTION)  ' DTC P1758 (TERMINAL 15 VOLTAGE SUPPLY OPEN CIRCUIT)  ' DTC P060A (INTERNAL CONTROL MODULE MONITORING PROCESSOR PERFORMANCE)  I DID SOME RESEARCH AND UNDERSTAND THERE IS A WELL KNOWN ISSUE WITH THE DSG TRANSMISSION, SPECIFICALLY WITH THE DRIVE POSITION SENSOR WHICH IS A VERY EXPENSIVE REPAIR TO HAVE DONE.

THE MECHATRONIC UNIT ON MY VEHICLE NEEDED TO BE REPLACED.  I WAS DRIVING AND A WARNING POPPED UP ON MY DASHBOARD SAYING "TRANSMISSION MALFUNCTION, YOU MAY CONTINUE DRIVING".  I WAS QUOTED $5000 FOR THE .  THIS IS A COMMON ISSUE NOT ONLY WITH MY MODEL, BUT ACROSS ALL AUDI MODELS WITH THE DSG TRANSMISSION.  AUDI CUSTOMERS SHOULD NOT BE FORCED TO PAY FOR AUDI PUTTING FAULTY EQUIPMENT IN THEIR VEHICLES.

THERE IS A WIDELY-KNOWN ISSUE IN 2013+ AUDI ELECTROMECHANICAL POWER STEERING THAT CREATES A SENSATION OF A "NOTCH" AT 12:00 ON THE STEERING WHEEL. THIS NOTCH FORCES YOU TO MANUALLY KEEP THE CAR IN THE LANE BY STEERING "BACK AND FORTH IN THE NOTCH". WHEN YOU TURN "BEYOND THE NOTCH" THERE IS A STICKING POINT. THE FASTER THE CAR IS MOVING, THE MORE PRONOUNCED THESE FEELINGS BECOME. I HAD HOPED THAT MY ISSUE WAS RELATED TO THE TIRES. UNFORTUNATELY, WAITING TO PURCHASE NEW TIRES HAS TAKEN ME OUT OF WARRANTY. AFTER JUST INSTALLING NEW CONTINENTAL DWS 06, THE PROBLEM IS AS BAD, OR WORSE, THAN IT HAS EVER BEEN. THIS IS INCREDIBLY DANGEROUS! RESEARCHING ONLINE, MANY, MANY PEOPLE HAVE THIS PROBLEM.    HERE IS A LINK TO AN INTERNET FORUM WHERE SOME INFORMATION HAS BEEN CONSOLIDATED:    HTTPS://WWW.AUDIWORLD.COM/FORUMS/A6-C7-PLATFORM-DISCUSSION-194/AUDI-ELECTRIC-STEERING-ISSUE-REPORTS-CONSOLIDATED-2844976

THE RS5 HAD A VERY BED PROBLEM WITH THE BREAKS. WHEN I WAS USING THE BREAKS THE CAR WAS SHACKING, ESPECIALLY WHEN I USED THE BREAK AT THE SPEED OF 75/80 MPH. THE CAR WAS UNSAFE AND TO STOP COMPLETELY THE CAR I HAD TO GO OUT OF THE STREET.  ON NOVEMBER 2013 I LEFT THE RS A5 AT THE DEALER IN GREENSBORO. ON THE AFTERNOON I WAS CONTACTED BY AN ADVISOR OF THE AUDI SERVICE IN GREENSBORO. THIS ADVISOR TOLD ME THAT MY CAR NEEDED NEW PADS AND NEW ROTOR AND THAT THESE PARTS SUPPOSES TO COME  FROM GERMANY AND THE WAIT TO HAVE THIS PARTS WAS 2 WEEKS.  THE SERVICE ADVISOR TOLD ME THAT DURING THESE 2 WEEKS I COULD DRIVE MY CAR. WHEN I TOLD HIM THAT THE PROBLEM WITH THE BREAKS WAS VERY BED ESPECIALLY AT 80 MPH HE ANSWERS ME BACK THAT THE SPEED LIMIT IS 65 MPH.  WHEN I WENT TO PICK MY CAR UP  FROM THE DEALER IN GREENSBORO AND WHEN I TOLD THE SERVICE ADVISOR THAT DRIVING OVER THE SPEED LIMIT WAS MY PROBLEM AND THAT THE CAR IS SUPPOSED TO HANDLED HIGHER SPEED THAN 80 MPH HE WAS VERY UNPOLITE AND HE TROUGH THE DOCUMENT OF MY CAR ON THE DESK.  WHEN I TOLD HIM THAT HE HAD TO BE POLITE WITH CUSTOMERS  HE TOLD ME '*** YOU'. MY REACTION WASN'T REALLY POLITE AND HE TOLD ME AGAIN '*** YOU' AND HE WAS INTIMIDATING ME. ONLY THE INTERVENTION OF THE MANAGER OF THE SERVICE AT THE LOCATION STOPPED HIM.  AFTER THIS ISSUE FLOW AUDI OF GREENSBORO (NC) CHANGED THE FRONT ROTORS AND PADS, 2 WEEKS WAITING. IN FEBRUARY 2014, AFTER ONLY 2000 MILES, THE CAR HAD THE SAME PROBLEMS AND THE SERVICE MANAGER AT AUDI TOLD ME THAT THE BACK ROTORS AND PADS NEEDED TO BE CHANGED.  AFTER THE SECOND REPLACEMENT, ON MARCH 2013, THE PROBLEM WASN'T SOLVED AND I WENT AGAIN TO THE AUDI DEALER SERVICE, I ALSO WROTE SEVERAL TIME TO THE AUDI CUSTOMER SERVICE.  AT THE END OF MARCH THE MANAGER OF THE AUDI SERVICE IN GREENSBORO TOLD ME THAT THE PROBLEM WITH MY CAR WAS NORMAL.  *TR

issues.title: Carbon Build-up on Intake Valves
issues.description: Direct injection engines accumulate carbon deposits on intake valves due to lack of fuel washing over the valves, causing reduced performance and rough idle
issues.fix_description: Professional walnut blasting or chemical cleaning of intake valves every 40,000-60,000 miles
issues.prevention: Use top-tier gasoline, drive highway speeds regularly, consider catch can installation

issues.title: Timing Chain Tensioner Failure
issues.description: Upper timing chain tensioner can fail, causing rattling noise and potential catastrophic engine damage if chain jumps timing
issues.fix_description: Replace timing chain tensioner, guides, and chain as preventive measure or complete engine rebuild if damage occurred
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes with proper specification oil, listen for unusual startup noises

issues.title: PCV Valve and Diverter Valve Failure
issues.description: Positive Crankcase Ventilation valve and turbocharger diverter valves commonly fail, causing boost leaks and rough running
issues.fix_description: Replace PCV valve and diverter valve with updated parts
issues.prevention: Regular maintenance and inspection of vacuum lines and boost system components

issues.title: Water Pump Failure
issues.description: Plastic impeller water pumps are prone to failure, leading to coolant leaks and potential engine overheating
issues.fix_description: Replace water pump, thermostat, and coolant. Consider upgrading to metal impeller aftermarket unit
issues.prevention: Regular coolant system maintenance and monitoring coolant levels

issues.title: Ignition Coil Pack Failure
issues.description: Ignition coil packs fail frequently, causing misfires and reduced engine performance
issues.fix_description: Replace failed ignition coil packs and spark plugs as a set
issues.prevention: Use OEM or high-quality replacement coils, replace spark plugs at recommended intervals

issues.title: Fuel Injector Failure
issues.description: Direct injection fuel injectors can fail due to carbon buildup and high pressure operation, causing misfires and poor performance
issues.fix_description: Professional injector cleaning or replacement of failed injectors
issues.prevention: Use quality fuel, regular fuel system cleaning, avoid extended idle periods

issues.title: Supercharger Belt and Pulley Issues
issues.description: Supercharger drive belt and pulleys can wear prematurely, causing squealing noises and potential loss of supercharger function
issues.fix_description: Replace supercharger belt, tensioner, and pulleys as needed
issues.prevention: Regular inspection of belt condition and proper belt tension maintenance

issues.title: Oil Leak from Valve Cover Gaskets
issues.description: Valve cover gaskets deteriorate over time, causing oil leaks onto the exhaust manifold and creating burning oil smell
issues.fix_description: Replace valve cover gaskets and clean oil residue from engine components
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes and monitoring for early signs of gasket deterioration

issues.title: Thermostat Housing Failure
issues.description: Plastic thermostat housing can crack or warp, leading to coolant leaks and temperature regulation issues
issues.fix_description: Replace thermostat housing, thermostat, and refill cooling system
issues.prevention: Regular coolant system maintenance and avoid extreme temperature conditions

issues.title: DSG Transmission Mechatronic Unit Issues
issues.description: DSG dual-clutch transmission mechatronic control unit can fail, causing harsh shifts, slipping, or complete transmission failure
issues.fix_description: Replace or rebuild mechatronic unit, update transmission software, replace transmission fluid
issues.prevention: Regular DSG service every 40,000 miles, avoid aggressive driving when cold

issues.title: Brake Pad Wear Sensors Malfunction
issues.description: Electronic brake pad wear sensors frequently fail or give false readings, triggering brake warning lights prematurely
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty brake pad wear sensors and reset brake monitoring system
issues.prevention: Regular brake inspection and replacement of sensors during brake pad changes

issues.title: Fuel Pump High Pressure Issues
issues.description: High-pressure fuel pump can fail, causing fuel starvation, reduced performance, and potential engine damage
issues.fix_description: Replace high-pressure fuel pump and low-pressure fuel pump as precautionary measure
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, avoid running on very low fuel levels, regular fuel filter replacement

editorial.tagline: Naturally aspirated V8 swan song perfection
editorial.hero_blurb: The B8 RS5 represents the final chapter of Audi's naturally aspirated V8 era, delivering 450 horsepower through one of the most characterful engines ever fitted to a road car. This is raw, unfiltered performance wrapped in elegant Ingolstadt sophistication.
editorial.essence: The B8 RS5 is automotive poetry in motion, combining Audi's legendary quattro all-wheel drive with a screaming 4.2-liter V8 that revs to 8,250 rpm. It's the last of its kind - a naturally aspirated masterpiece that prioritizes character over pure efficiency.
editorial.heritage: Born from Audi's RS lineage that began with the original RS2 Avant in 1994, the RS5 carries forward the tradition of high-performance grand tourers. This B8 generation marked the final use of Audi's beloved naturally aspirated V8 before turbocharging took over.
editorial.design_philosophy: Audi's designers aimed to create a sophisticated predator - muscular yet refined, with flared wheel arches and aggressive styling cues that hint at the beast within while maintaining the elegant proportions of a luxury coupe.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not directly derived from racing, the RS5 shares DNA with Audi's successful DTM and endurance racing programs, incorporating lessons learned from decades of quattro all-wheel drive development in motorsport.
editorial.engine_character: The 4.2-liter FSI V8 is pure theater - it builds power linearly and dramatically, with a crescendo that peaks near its 8,250 rpm redline. It's responsive, eager, and delivers power with the kind of immediacy that only naturally aspirated engines can provide.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 7-speed S tronic dual-clutch transmission fires off shifts with precision and aggression, particularly in Dynamic mode. Manual mode offers satisfying paddle control, though the transmission is intelligent enough to hold gears during spirited driving.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The quattro all-wheel drive system provides unshakeable confidence, while the sport differential and adaptive suspension create a chassis that's equally at home carving canyons or consuming highway miles with refined composure.
editorial.steering_feel: Audi's electromechanical steering offers good precision and reasonable feedback, though it lacks the ultimate communication of hydraulic systems. Weight builds naturally with speed, providing confidence-inspiring feel through corners.
editorial.brake_confidence: The massive brakes provide excellent stopping power with a firm, progressive pedal feel. They're well-suited to both spirited driving and track days, with minimal fade under hard use.
editorial.sound_signature: The naturally aspirated V8 produces one of the greatest automotive symphonies ever recorded - a deep, rumbling idle that transforms into a spine-tingling wail as it climbs toward redline, punctuated by aggressive pops and crackles on overrun.
editorial.ideal_owner: The enthusiast who appreciates naturally aspirated character over outright speed numbers, someone who values the theater and emotion of driving over pure efficiency.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Buyers seeking maximum fuel economy, those who prioritize straight-line acceleration over engine character, or drivers who rarely explore the upper reaches of the rev range.
editorial.buyers_summary: Look for well-maintained examples with full service history, as these engines reward proper care. The carbon fiber roof option and sport differential are highly desirable features that enhance both performance and desirability.
